a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"LiDAR shrinks from mirrors to microchips"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"SWaP tradeoffs redefined for deep-space missions"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"MIT-Sandia collaboration targets laser comms bottleneck"}]]}]]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Every gram launched into orbit is a negotiation. For decades, that negotiation has been particularly fraught around LiDAR and laser communications systems, where bulky mechanical mirrors—heavy, power-hungry, and prone to failure—have been the price of precision. But a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07523-0","children":["paper published in ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Nature"}]]}]," this week from researchers at MIT, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.mitre.org/","children":"MITRE"}],", and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.sandia.gov/","children":"Sandia National Laboratories"}]," introduces a radical alternative: a ‘photonic ski-jump’ that steers light without moving parts.\nThe concept replaces traditional mirrors with microscopic, static structures etched onto a chip. These structures—resembling the angled ramps of a ski jump—bend light beams purely through their geometry, eliminating the need for motors, gimbals, or calibration systems. Early tests suggest the design could reduce a LiDAR system’s volume by orders of magnitude while slashing power demands. For spacecraft, where ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nasa.gov/directorates/heo/scan/services/swap/","children":"Size, Weight, and Power (SWaP) constraints"}]," dictate mission viability, this isn’t incremental improvement. It’s a potential reset.\nThe timing is critical. NASA’s ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nasa.gov/specials/artemis/","children":"Artemis program"}]," and commercial lunar landers are already pushing against SWaP limits, while future Mars missions will demand even lighter, more efficient systems for terrain mapping and high-bandwidth comms. If the ski-jump design scales as predicted, it could unblock bottlenecks in everything from autonomous lunar rovers to deep-space data relays."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/how-photonic-ski-jumps-could-rewrite-spacecraft-de/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A 50-year problem in optical systems may have just met its match—no moving parts required.","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"A 50-year problem in optical systems may have just met its match—no moving parts required."}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["Yet the real significance lies in what this ",["$","em",null,{"children":"isn’t"}],": a fundamental physics breakthrough, but an engineering one. The team—led by MIT’s ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.rle.mit.edu/people/juejun-hu/","children":"Juejun Hu"}],"—leveraged existing photonic principles, repurposing them for a problem that had stumped optical engineers since the 1970s. ‘We’re not inventing new science,’ Hu noted in a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://news.mit.edu/2024/photonic-ski-jump-lidar-spacecraft-0612","children":"statement"}],", ‘we’re eliminating the need for the mechanical parts that made old solutions so cumbersome.’\nThat elimination has cascading effects. Without moving mirrors, systems become more robust against vibration—a chronic issue during launch—and require far less maintenance. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07523-0","children":"paper’s simulations"}]," project efficiency gains of 30–50% over traditional designs, though real-world testing in thermal vacuums and radiation environments remains pending. Sandia’s role in the collaboration hints at defense applications too, where SWaP-efficient LiDAR could enable smaller, stealthier satellites.\nThe next 12 months will be telling. The team plans to prototype the design for ","$L13",", which funds high-risk, high-reward space tech. If those tests confirm the lab results, the ski-jump could appear in missions by the late 2020s—just as lunar and Martian traffic ramps up. The question then shifts from ","$L14"," this works to ","$L15"," it can be deployed."]}]]}]
